    <img src="media/freedom-handcuffs-hands-247851.png" class="img-fluid" alt="eudpr">
    <h1 class="mt-5">GDPR — You don’t own me</h1>
    <div class="row my-5">
      <div class="d-inline col-lg-6">
        <img src="https://eudpr.com/profile/rem.jpg" class="float-left rounded-circle mr-3" alt="RemyWilders" height="48">
        <div>Remy Wilders<a href="https://twitter.com/RemyWilders" target="_blank"><i class="fab fa-twitter ml-1 text-dark"></i></a><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/remy-wilders-159320/" target="_blank"><i class="fab fa-linkedin ml-1 text-dark"></i></a><br /><span class="text-muted">April 14, 2019</span></div>
      </div>
      <div class="d-block pt-3 d-lg-none">&emsp;</div>
      <div class="d-inline col-lg-6">
        <!--<audio controls>
          <source src="media/audio_gdpr-what-to-expect-from-your-eu-representative.ogg" type="audio/ogg">
          Your browser does not support the audio element.
        </audio>-->
      </div>
    </div>
    <p>Many years back, when I was “so much younger than today”, a very good friend of mine lent me a Klaus Nomi record. I didn’t know this artist and was immediately fascinated by his opera rock music and his incredible voice.</p>
    <p>Among the titles there was one which comes back to me regularly when helping companies out with their GDPR, the title is “You don’t own me”. The lyrics go on to say “You don’t own me, I’m not just one of your little toys”.</p>
    <p>This claim has always seemed to me as the best way to coin the GDPR’s mission. Companies need to understand the power of the personal data and how, if abused, it can turn out to be a handle for manipulating their clients and users. To be even more dramatic one could say “to own their digital souls”.</p>
    <p>Imagine that a friend of yours trusted you with the keys to his home. Would you add a label to these keys with the name and address of your friend? Would you then simply leave the keys hanging around? If you did so and that the keys were stolen, would you not be somewhat responsible? Should your friend trust you with his keys again?</p>
    <p>In fact user names and passwords can, in some instances, turn out to be even more valuable than someone’s keys. Even if your site does not contain any sensitive information you can be sure that many of your users are using the same username and password on your site as they are on other sites which may contain precious information. So if somebody gets a hold of your users’ usernames and passwords, they will have access to many user spaces on other sites. This is the reason why it is so important for all sites to be GDPR compliant even if the only personal data you hold are user names, passwords and email addresses.</p>
    <p>Users should understand that a GDPR compliant site accepts to declare a data breach within 72 hours. This should give time, to most of the users, to change their passwords on other sites. Declaring a data breach will not entail a fine for the site (except if the security was absent such as the “Admin/Password” login) so everybody wins with GDPR compliance. On the other hand users should really stay away from GDPR non-compliant sites.</p>
    <p>But how can one know whether a company plays the right game or not? Well it is quite simple in fact. Look up the word GDPR within the site and see what comes up. If nothing comes up you should move away. If the word does come up look at the user rights that they declare you have (access, modification, erasure, portability…) and how you can put them into action. If the website is outside of Europe check for their European representative as it is mandatory. If they do not mention one and do not provide the contact details the best is to avoid trusting your data to this site. Finally you can write to the site to ask them about their GDPR policy.</p>
    <p>You may think to yourself that if you are not an EU user you are not really concerned with all this GDPR business. The truth is that you probably should be, because if a site is GDPR compliant it will probably be so for all of its users and is therefore safer than a site which has not thought these matters through.</p>
    <p>The power of data is quite mind boggling if you look into it and regulations such as the GDPR should be more than welcome in our ever more digital world.</p>
    <hr>
